message.content:
**Plugin developers**: I'm currently working on designing some of the core APIs, which includes the injector, settings and so on, and I need feedback™️ regarding injection IDs (and IDs in general for settings, etc..). I'll mostly talk about injecting but it'll also apply to the rest.

As of right now, plugins have to define IDs themselves, and put a unique prefix themselves to ensure there are no conflicts. They also have to explicitly unload everything explicitly in the plugin unload function.

So, my 2 questions are: what'd be the best way to handle IDs, and should we keep uninjecting an explicit action the plugin is required to do or do we do it automatically?

I'll probably at least do something to prepend IDs with a unique identifier to avoid any possible conflicts (and therefore plugin probing), but I'm also thinking about making the ID generation completely automatic, and have it as the return of the inject function. What'd you folks prefer?

----
Regarding uninjecting, doing it explicitly will remain something plugins will be able to do no matter what, but would it be a good idea to uninject & unregister stuff automatically (reducing the risk of developer forgetting stuff), or it's better to keep it as it currently is?

On one hand, having everything explicit makes everything consistent for sure, but leads to the devs having to care about more stuff
On the other hand, implicit uninjections makes devs life easier, but is inconsistent with event listeners and various stuff done outside of Powercord-provided APIs.


=> Share your thoughts and express yourself in <#765598447813918820>
**Current feedback**:
Manual IDs: 1
Automatic IDs: 1

Manual uninject: 4
Automatic uninject: 3
